{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T17:16:03.442860", "elapsed_seconds": 14.487, "stage": "INFO", "message": "Generated response from Gemini", "data": {"response": "To create a POST endpoint, you would define a \"path operation\" which is also commonly called an \"endpoint\" or a \"route\" (Documents 1, 6, 11).\n\nWhen a client sends data to your API, it's often sent as a \"request body\" (Documents 26, 31). To receive this data in your path operation, you declare it as a parameter, similar to how path and query parameters are declared. You would specify its type as a model you've created.\n\nFor example, to receive an `Item` in a path operation, you would declare it like this:\n```python\nasync def create_item(item: Item):\n    return item\n```\n(Document 86)\n\nThe context does not provide the full decorator syntax (e.g., `@app.post(\"/your-path\")`) for a standard POST endpoint, but it does show how to define the function that handles the request body for a path operation. It also shows an example of defining webhooks using `@app.webhooks.post()` (Documents 56, 61).", "response_length": 899, "tokens_used": 149, "sources_extracted": ["Source: docs\\tutorial\\first-steps.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\request-forms.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\body.md", "Source: docs\\advanced\\openapi-webhooks.md", "Source: docs\\advanced\\openapi-callbacks.md", "Source: docs\\advanced\\middleware.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\index.md", "Source: docs\\advanced\\response-change-status-code.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\schema-extra-example.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\testing.md", "Source: docs\\tutorial\\response-status-code.md"]}}
